The original is a one of one so we decided to do a limited edition print for her highness to bless more of all of our spaces and help CLEAN YOUR WIBES.

A labour of love. Our sister and favourite visual artist @rajniperera came to visit our India studio years ago and painted this beauty. It took us a meditative pandemic year to create the iconic tapestry of our dreams. Hand embroidered in a spectrum of techniques by Mustak Bhai, the real embroidery legend.

Rajni Perera was born in Sri Lanka and lives and works in Toronto. She explores issues of hybridity, futurity, ancestorship, immigration identity/cultures, monsters and dream worlds. All of these themes marry in a newly objectified realm of mythical symbioses. In her work she seeks to open and reveal the dynamism of the icons and objects she creates, both scripturally existent, self-invented and externally defined. She creates a subversive aesthetic that counteracts antiquated, oppressive discourse, and acts as a restorative force through which people can move outdated, repressive modes of being towards reclaiming their power.

Mustak bhai from Hawra, Bengal started developing his embroidery craft with his mother since he was in the 6th grade. After graduating school he got into his practice full time, starting with Zardozi and then moving into more complex Aari needlework that requires more steady hand control and practice.

He is a self taught artist and has mastered both types of embroidery apparatus along with khaka creation which makes him a rare one man show.In this tapestry these are few of the majorly highlighted embroidery techniques used: 

Zari embroidery with hand twisted dori of 12 strands, Tufting done by hand with Aari needlework, Dabka on jaali-work style with fine-coiled copper wire and Mukesh work and Bead-work embroidery in jaali-work style.

Digital Print on Archival Paper of the Tapestry | Series of 100 limited edition prints.

A very cool thing happened that one time in Delhi. 

In 2019 I travelled to Shah Pur Jat to work with my friends @norblacknorwhite (hai baybesies) and we came up with the idea for a textile work. I hadn’t worked at all with textile yet and was feeling just  like a baby surrounded by delicious food at all times. 

We pored through all their found/made/scrap fabric and I came up with a little sketch called ‘Clean Your Wibes’, inspired by wibes, cricket, and the intense air pollution there that people were starting to wear masks for. This was the year before Covid. 

The embroidered tapestry was completed late last year by multifaceted master Mustak Bhai and is now hanging in their flagship store in Delhi. 

About Mustak Bhai (from NBNW):

Mustak bhai from Hawra, Bengal started developing his embroidery craft with his mother since he was in the 6th grade. After graduating school he got into his practice full time, starting with Zardozi and then moving into more complex Aari needlework that requires more steady hand control and practice. He is a self taught artist and has mastered both types of embroidery apparatus along with khaka creation which makes him a rare one man show.

In this tapestry are a few of the majorly highlighted embroidery techniques used, such as 
Zari embroidery with hand twisted dori of 12 strands, tufting with Aari needlework, Dabka on jaal-work style with fine-coiled copper wire, Mukesh work and Bead-work embroidery in jaali-style.

Coming Home.
We took a trip to photographer Baljit Singh's ancestral home and pind (village) Karyam, Punjab.

We DMd @bsinghh when we saw she was visiting her family in Punjab as we've been admirers of her portraits from afar. We got a good vibe from our initial chats and decided to plan a shoot. From IG to whatsapp to a studio visit with some of her family that we end up shooting in this series, our co-founder, Amrit took the train to spend the weekend with Baljit and her family in Karyam, Punjab.

The weekend was spent walking around the pind, listening to her fatherly stories, eating, laughing and getting to know family just the way we love to, up close and immersed. A common theme of our chats was about each our ideas on what “Coming Home" means.

The images in this collaborative series showcase home, family, and Punjab shot by Baljit Singh with NorBlack NorWhite. We share some parallel experiences of growing up as diaspora in the Toronto area so it all felt pretty full circle. 
 
In this image, sisters, Ritu (15 years old) and Gauri (11 years old) from Karyam, Punjab.

"My relationship with my ancestral home and the pind growing up was based on the handful of times I visited.

You know, you hear the stories from your parents, from your grandparents, on how it was back home, but to fully understand those stories as a child was difficult. 

And you try to reconnect and kind of vicariously live through the memories that your parents had and the stories they used to tell. But I feel like the older you get and the more you spend time here, you actually start realizing the significance of those actual stories and the time that they spent in their home and how important it is to document their stories.

Once you start understanding the history of even your own family, I think it really allows you to come to a better place of understanding yourself and where you want to go as an individual and how you want to weave that story, their journey into your craft." - Baljit Singh @bsinghh

Baljit Singh is a photographer based in Toronto, Canada. Her background in content creation allows her to work on projects that aim to document brown bodies while exploring themes of nostalgia, immigration, and social issues in the South Asian community. Baljit is the co-founder of The Kollective, a creative agency and production company that is committed to building young creatives.

In this image, Jassi (30 years old), Baljit's cousin from Karyam, Punjab. 

Coming Home. The images in this collaborative series showcase home, family, and Punjab shot by Baljit Singh with NorBlack NorWhite in Karyam, Punjab.

We love a BIBI.
Granny, Dadi, Ammama, Abeula, Lola, Nonna, Nani. Whatever you call them, there is an unmatched realness that comes with spending time with elders, whether they are set in their frustrating ways or are too cute to cope with, they are undeniably a wealth of experience that somehow always humbles.

Happy Vaisakhi, Happy Bday Ambedkar, Happy Bihu! Happy Puthandu! Happy Friday!

From the series, Coming Home. The images in this collaborative series showcase home, family, and Punjab shot by @bsinghh with NorBlack NorWhite in Karyam, Punjab.

Bibi, Harbans Kaur (76 years old) from Karyam, Punjab is wearing a custom NBNW Icicle Dipped Salwar Kameez with the Checks Gamcha Tunic.

“Punjab is full of such a rich culture of role models when it comes to our gurus. Moreover, freedom fighters, leaders, activists in our community, that plays such a significant role of the history of Punjab that no matter if you are needed to the land or if you're visiting, I think you can definitely feel the energy and the spirit of our people.

Punjab is so much part of our identity, even if we've never been there, even if we don't live there, I think we carry it so heavily as Punjabis in the way we move, live, work, speak and behave.

I think that plays a key role, especially for me as an artist and the importance of me wanting to document our people, especially to make sure that they're included in mainstream media in whatever way and whatever chance that they get, whether it's working with bigger brands and including faces of a young, gutti boy amongst the other faces….just breaking those barriers. “ - Baljit Singh @bsinghh

In this image, Bindi (14 years old), studies in the 10th from Karyam, Punjab. Wearing NBNW hand embroidered working sample.

From the series, Coming Home. The images in this collaborative series showcase home, family, and Punjab shot by @bsinghh with NorBlack NorWhite in Karyam, Punjab.

“Taking the train to go spend the weekend with Baljit and her family in Karyam, Punjab, felt like I had gone home to hang with my cousin and fam. The ease with which we got to know each other, the chats and laughs with her family just warmed my heart and reminded me so much of my very own back home. I felt like I was in both places, Toronto and Punjab, which is the beauty of the world we live in today. Home is many things and it’s the people that really make it what it is. Thank you to Baljit and her family for having us in their home and repping that NBNW with so much love.” - Amrit (Co-Founder NBNW)

Hargurjit Singh (57 years old) living in Mississauga, Canada + Kulwinder Singh (56 years old) living in Karyam, Punjab, cousin brothers.

NBNW 4 ALL 🥭
Slow and steady, made with 100% pure love, life is a moodboard, handmade everything 🤲🏾

Manpreet Kaur, age 28, a grade 11&12 biology teacher from Karyam, Punjab.

Getting ready for the shoot at Manpreet's parents home was too sweet, as she had just got married and had shifted to a neighbouring town with limited belongings of hers around. But in the moments leading up to it, in the midst of trying to avoid the rain and not wanting to miss the light, felt like getting her ready for a mini express wedding itself.

We asked cousins and neighbours for what jewellery they may have, we tried some different lip shades to see what worked, getting her ready in the guest room on the terrace, laughing away. And in typical wedding fashion her groom awaited his bride downstairs, with his car ready to escort us to our shooting locations, seeing her final look as the newly wed exchanged shy glances of approval.

We decided to layer the Joy is Real Dress with her shaadi look, the only thing missing was a glass bottle of Maaza.

From New Delhi to New York, @norblacknorwhite is coming to Sabah House New York on Friday, July 21 ☀️ 

But first - I want to take you to New Delhi and introduce you to the hyper-creative, culture shaping, and deeply original: NorBlack NorWhite. 

Built on a sweet friendship between co-founders and creative directors, Amrit Kumar & Mriga Kapadiya -- NorBlack NorWhite is a New Delhi-based design house that studies India's rich history of textile & craft to bring forward beautiful textile driven apparel collections built on artisanship, color & pattern. The work speaks for iteslf -- really original with a value system & mindset I find quite inspiring too (see “About” on their website).

They'll be taking up residence at Sabah House New York, July 21-30, and offering a collection, shared in this post, especially designed for their time with us. That collection draws from NBNW favorites: tie dye, hand embroidery, block printing and handloom ikat weaves, inspired by everything from the street snack chutneys & Bombay skies to the varied terrains of India & textiles from Assam. 

So we hope to see y'all at Sabah House New York starting next Friday, or... for our Sabah Sunday in celebration of this partnership from 2-6PM on Sunday July 23 (more on that soon … we have a very, very special DJ set by @lidopimienta 🎶 )! Until then! #howwesabah #wheretonext

Respect the process, respect the roses! 🌹 Each Shirt takes 12 hours to just embroider, so this ain't no joke thing. Here's how it goes down:

Step 1 - The fabric is a handwoven Khadi cotton, woven in Bengal.

Step 2 - Each rose petal fabric is individually dyed (that's 7 different colours!)

Step 3 - Each one is cut into teeny pieces to create the petal shapes.

Step 4 - The petals are then patched onto the pattern to create the pretty rose shapes.

Step 5 - Our embroiders decoratively line each rose to keep the lines sharp.

Step 6 - After all the roses are embroidered on the fabric, it's ready to be cut and stitched!

BOMBBS © SINCE 2013 - MEHEK MALHOTRA @giggling_monkey 

This collector-gatherer of stories + impressions + emotions has been living in the city for a decade now, and is enjoying her last few months of chaos before she packs all her belongings for a garden home up north. 

Here's her list of Bombay Faves: 

Sight 👁 - Lovers intertwining fingers and sharing whispers agains the backdrop of marine Drive or Bandstand. 
Sound 👂🏾 - the soft, rhythmic jingle of the paowala's bicycle as he makes his morning rounds + the infectious carolling around Christmas time (bum notes and all!)

Snack 🍽 - mango ice-cream from natural’s on Marine Drive if it’s 🥭 season, otherwise malai. 
Szn ☀️ - That particular sliver of January when the air feels gentler and we get a break from the humidity. Feels like birthday gift every year!

This Double Cotton Ikat is created by a technique that resist-ties and dyes both the warp & weft, making it a very intricate process. We have 15 colours going on here, so just imagine! The threads are then carefully and meticulously added to the loom, this alone takes 25 days. Where the weaver then slowly and steadily handweaves the beautiful multi-coloured pattern to form & create what we now love and call Dance Dance Ikat.

We first discovered this handwoven textile masterpiece from Assam 10 years ago during our travels and it’s become that special piece which journeys with us on EVERY travel since! A true staple that takes on many shapes and styles. 

The weaving process of the Matix Xaal (Matix = Earth & Xaal = Loom) by the women of the Mising Tribe, is a cherished tradition passed down through generations. This specific textile, the Gero, represents not only the artistic expression of the weavers but also the cultural heritage of the region. We spent years looking for the right partners to work with, until earlier this year when we headed to Assam for the annual Mising Autonomous Council’s Handloom Expo, where we met and teamed up with an aunt & niece duo working with 20 weavers from Lakhimpur who bring these beauties to life.

We’re so honoured to present their vision and tradition in the form of one of our favourite NBNW pieces to date!

We recently had the honour of meeting Lika Aunty @likag_helio, our friend @mandopie24 actual aunty and by extension she is now ours too! 🥹

Self-proclaimed ‘Sun Goddess’ & ‘Alien,’ her mind and heart fly *very* close to both the sun and the Indian subcontinent; as an astrophysicist who loves her science as much as she does her Bangla poetry + music. 

We spent a very sunny morning in Goa with a streak of fierce Bengali Tigresses eating homemade dosas and coffee, shooting candids and laughing our way through all the harsh truths. We discovered Lika’s spice rack has remained 200% Indian and that she still slips into Bengali when she gets real mad or feels particularly loving, even after more than 30 years living away from home. 

Hearts feel as full sharing these, as they were when we took them. AUNTIES 4EVA 🌹
